stylometry:
The probability distributions include NORMAL - providing mean, and standard deviation; TRIANGULAR - mean, minimum, maximum; and DISCRETE - values, whole numbers and probabilities.

Discrete - involves the uniqueness of probabilities; I found this to be a great way in making a decision because the problem I worked on gave it to you in a chart/table format values on one side and the probabilities on the other. In these types of problems we found that using riskdiscrete was essential. You also have a few other determining factors like multiple revenues, left over revenues, etc. Also deferring one probability from the other; like in Bayes' theorum where when new information is provided the previous probabilities are turned. The risk here, in discrete probability distribution is that of the fact it's a probability something will happen; so basing your decision off of a high or low probability may not be as exact as a normal or triangular distribution problem.
